  "statement": "# Evaluate Reverse Polish Notation\n\nEvaluate an arithmetic expression written in Reverse Polish Notation. Division truncates toward zero.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: tokens = [\"2\", \"1\", \"+\", \"3\", \"*\"]\nOutput: 9\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: tokens = [\"4\", \"13\", \"5\", \"/\", \"+\"]\nOutput: 6\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: tokens = [\"10\", \"6\", \"9\", \"3\", \"+\", \"-11\", \"*\", \"/\", \"*\", \"17\", \"+\", \"5\", \"+\"]\nOutput: 22\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Input sizes follow the original interview-style constraints.\n- Return values must match the described behavior.",
  "editorial": "Use a stack to keep unresolved items. When a new token, bar, or value resolves earlier items, pop them and update the answer.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def evalRPN(self, tokens):\n        stack = []\n        for token in tokens:\n            if token not in '+-*/':\n                stack.append(int(token))\n                continue\n            b = stack.pop()\n            a = stack.pop()\n            if token == '+':\n                stack.append(a + b)\n            elif token == '-':\n                stack.append(a - b)\n            elif token == '*':\n                stack.append(a * b)\n            else:\n                stack.append(int(a / b))\n        return stack[-1]\n```",
  "hints": [
    "A stack is useful when the most recent unresolved item should be handled first.",
    "Keep extra state on the stack when constant-time queries are needed."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def evalRPN(self, tokens):\n        pass\n"
  },
